WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.326 --> 00:00:03.100
LOGAN URY: So thanks
for joining us today.

00:00:03.100 --> 00:00:04.190
My name is Logan Ury.

00:00:04.190 --> 00:00:06.370
I'm really excited to have
Gretchen Rubin with us.

00:00:06.370 --> 00:00:08.780
I actually work in a team
called the Irrational Lab

00:00:08.780 --> 00:00:11.350
and we study human behavior
and products at Google.

00:00:11.350 --> 00:00:13.890
So I'm particularly interested
in all of Gretchen's work,

00:00:13.890 --> 00:00:15.980
and we're lucky enough to
have her with us today.

00:00:15.980 --> 00:00:18.240
I'll ask some questions
until around 1:40,

00:00:18.240 --> 00:00:20.330
and then I'll open it up to you.

00:00:20.330 --> 00:00:23.470
So Gretchen Rubin is one of the
most provoking and influential

00:00:23.470 --> 00:00:26.380
writers on the linked
subjects of happiness, habits,

00:00:26.380 --> 00:00:27.690
and human nature.

00:00:27.690 --> 00:00:30.150
She's the author of many
books, including "The New York

00:00:30.150 --> 00:00:32.189
Times" best sellers
"The Happiness Project"

00:00:32.189 --> 00:00:33.720
and "Happier at Home."

00:00:33.720 --> 00:00:36.400
Rubin has an enormous
following in print and online,

00:00:36.400 --> 00:00:39.370
and her books have sold more
than a million copies worldwide

00:00:39.370 --> 00:00:41.370
in more than 30 languages.

00:00:41.370 --> 00:00:43.270
Rubin started her
career in law and was

00:00:43.270 --> 00:00:46.180
clerking for Justice Sandra
Day O'Connor when she realized

00:00:46.180 --> 00:00:47.900
she wanted to be a writer.

00:00:47.900 --> 00:00:50.660
She lives in New York City with
her husband and two daughters.

00:00:50.660 --> 00:00:52.685
Ladies and gentlemen,
I'm pleased to introduce

00:00:52.685 --> 00:00:53.740
Gretchen Rubin.

00:00:53.740 --> 00:00:56.200
[APPLAUSE]

00:00:57.184 --> 00:01:00.510
GRETCHEN RUBIN: Well, I'm
very happy to be here.

00:01:00.510 --> 00:01:02.010
LOGAN URY: So I
want to start just

00:01:02.010 --> 00:01:03.590
by finding out
about the transition

00:01:03.590 --> 00:01:05.390
from clerking to
becoming a writer.

00:01:05.390 --> 00:01:07.034
What was that like?

00:01:07.034 --> 00:01:08.450
GRETCHEN RUBIN:
Well, I was lucky.

00:01:08.450 --> 00:01:10.172
Because a lot of
times, people know

00:01:10.172 --> 00:01:12.130
they don't want to do
something, but they don't

00:01:12.130 --> 00:01:13.880
know what they do want to do.

00:01:13.880 --> 00:01:20.640
And I was fortunate because one
day I was doing my clerkship

00:01:20.640 --> 00:01:22.260
and I was going for
walk at lunchtime

00:01:22.260 --> 00:01:25.580
and I was staring up the Capitol
dome against the blue sky.

00:01:25.580 --> 00:01:28.539
And I thought, if I
were to write something

00:01:28.539 --> 00:01:31.080
that was interesting to me, that
was interesting to everybody

00:01:31.080 --> 00:01:32.913
else in the world, what
would I write about?

00:01:32.913 --> 00:01:36.482
And I thought, power,
money, fame, sex.

00:01:36.482 --> 00:01:38.190
And all of a sudden
it hit me, and I just

00:01:38.190 --> 00:01:39.648
started this giant
research project

00:01:39.648 --> 00:01:41.490
on power, money, fame and sex.

00:01:41.490 --> 00:01:43.890
And I was doing it
in my free time.

00:01:43.890 --> 00:01:46.382
I was staying late at work
and I was working on it

00:01:46.382 --> 00:01:47.160
on the weekends.

00:01:47.160 --> 00:01:50.220
And finally it occurred to me
that this is the kind of thing

00:01:50.220 --> 00:01:51.370
that people do as a job.

00:01:51.370 --> 00:01:54.590
They write a book like
this as their job.

00:01:54.590 --> 00:01:56.190
And I was treating
it as a hobby.

00:01:56.190 --> 00:01:59.866
And then I thought well,
maybe I should do it as a job.

00:01:59.866 --> 00:02:01.240
And my husband
and I were getting

00:02:01.240 --> 00:02:06.680
ready to move to New York, and
I couldn't think of a law job

00:02:06.680 --> 00:02:07.570
that I wanted.

00:02:07.570 --> 00:02:11.330
Here I was, I had a lot of
feathers in my cap as lawyer,

00:02:11.330 --> 00:02:14.680
and I couldn't think of a
single law job that I wanted.

00:02:14.680 --> 00:02:17.830
So I thought, well you know,
I'd rather fail as a writer

00:02:17.830 --> 00:02:19.540
than succeed as a lawyer.

00:02:19.540 --> 00:02:22.770
And this is my time to do it
because I'm moving to New York.

00:02:22.770 --> 00:02:24.830
If I get a law job, I'll
probably never leave it.

00:02:24.830 --> 00:02:27.390
So I should try to
get a book written.

00:02:27.390 --> 00:02:29.140
And so that's when I
tried to get an agent

00:02:29.140 --> 00:02:31.000
and write a book
proposal and all that.

00:02:31.000 --> 00:02:33.319
LOGAN URY: So you moved from
money, fame, sex and power

00:02:33.319 --> 00:02:33.860
to happiness?

00:02:33.860 --> 00:02:36.310
GRETCHEN RUBIN: Well, in
between I wrote a book.

00:02:36.310 --> 00:02:40.980
So I know it sounds strange,
but really my real subject

00:02:40.980 --> 00:02:41.650
is human nature.

00:02:41.650 --> 00:02:43.691
That's the thing that's
always interesting to me.

00:02:43.691 --> 00:02:45.590
So I wrote about power,
money, fame, sex.

00:02:45.590 --> 00:02:48.260
It was called a user's
guide, and it's sort of

00:02:48.260 --> 00:02:51.560
like "The Preppy Handbook" for
power, money, fame, and sex.

00:02:51.560 --> 00:02:53.000
Sort of satirical.

00:02:53.000 --> 00:02:55.250
Then I wrote biographies of
Winston Churchill and JFK,

00:02:55.250 --> 00:02:57.900
because these are such
exaggerated-- they're so huge,

00:02:57.900 --> 00:03:00.600
you could see human
nature more clearly.

00:03:00.600 --> 00:03:04.017
I wrote this weird book
called "Profane Waste,"

00:03:04.017 --> 00:03:05.600
because for a long
time I was obsessed

00:03:05.600 --> 00:03:07.240
with the question
of why owners would

00:03:07.240 --> 00:03:09.460
destroy their own possessions.

00:03:09.460 --> 00:03:11.410
And then I got to "The
Happiness Project."

00:03:11.410 --> 00:03:13.300
But to me, they all
seem very interrelated.

00:03:13.300 --> 00:03:15.910
Even though from the outside,
it's sort of bizarre shifts.

00:03:15.910 --> 00:03:16.780
LOGAN URY: Yes.

00:03:16.780 --> 00:03:18.030
So I think a lot of
people in this room

00:03:18.030 --> 00:03:20.320
are really interested in
everything around happiness.

00:03:20.320 --> 00:03:22.220
What are some of the
biggest misconceptions

00:03:22.220 --> 00:03:24.785
around happiness?

00:03:24.785 --> 00:03:28.330
GRETCHEN RUBIN: Well, one
of the most complicated

00:03:28.330 --> 00:03:30.560
and emotionally charged
areas within happiness

00:03:30.560 --> 00:03:32.660
is the role of
money in happiness.

00:03:32.660 --> 00:03:35.730
And people will often say,
well, money can't buy happiness.

00:03:35.730 --> 00:03:36.770
And it can't.

00:03:36.770 --> 00:03:39.650
But it can buy a lot of things
that contribute powerfully

00:03:39.650 --> 00:03:41.000
to happiness.

00:03:41.000 --> 00:03:43.390
And so money has a
real role to play.

00:03:43.390 --> 00:03:45.900
But it's a question of how
are you spending your money?

00:03:45.900 --> 00:03:49.037
Because you could buy a bike,
or you could buy cocaine.

00:03:49.037 --> 00:03:51.370
And those are probably going
to have different outcomes.

00:03:51.370 --> 00:03:53.000
[LAUGHTER]

00:03:53.000 --> 00:03:54.990
And people have different needs.

00:03:54.990 --> 00:03:57.485
One person might have a lot
of people depending on them.

00:03:57.485 --> 00:04:00.180
And one person might
live alone with a turtle.

00:04:00.180 --> 00:04:02.070
And so the level
of money that would

00:04:02.070 --> 00:04:05.100
make them feel safe and
secure would be different.

00:04:05.100 --> 00:04:07.085
So one is related to money.

00:04:10.270 --> 00:04:14.570
And one, I think, is this
idea that certain things

00:04:14.570 --> 00:04:15.810
make people happy.

00:04:15.810 --> 00:04:17.290
Music makes people happy.

00:04:17.290 --> 00:04:18.709
Travel makes people happy.

00:04:18.709 --> 00:04:20.130
Shopping makes people happy.

00:04:20.130 --> 00:04:21.690
Wine makes people happy.

00:04:21.690 --> 00:04:24.700
None of those things
make me happy.

00:04:24.700 --> 00:04:27.014
There is no one size fits all.

00:04:27.014 --> 00:04:28.680
We all have to know
what makes us happy.

00:04:28.680 --> 00:04:30.870
And sometimes that's
surprisingly hard to do.

00:04:30.870 --> 00:04:32.726
So I think the idea
that there's something

00:04:32.726 --> 00:04:35.350
that we can all just point to--
except relationships, probably.

00:04:35.350 --> 00:04:37.227
Relationships do
make people happier.

00:04:37.227 --> 00:04:38.810
But what those
relationships look like

00:04:38.810 --> 00:04:40.080
are very different
for different people,

00:04:40.080 --> 00:04:41.795
depending on how
many relationships

00:04:41.795 --> 00:04:42.700
they like to have.

00:04:42.700 --> 00:04:44.740
LOGAN URY: So speaking
of what makes you happy,

00:04:44.740 --> 00:04:46.720
what single change that
you made in your life

00:04:46.720 --> 00:04:48.819
contributed the most to
your personal happiness?

00:04:48.819 --> 00:04:49.610
GRETCHEN RUBIN: Oh.

00:04:49.610 --> 00:04:51.620
Well, switching from being
a lawyer to a writer.

00:04:51.620 --> 00:04:52.117
LOGAN URY: Oh.

00:04:52.117 --> 00:04:53.111
GRETCHEN RUBIN: For sure.

00:04:53.111 --> 00:04:53.610
Yeah.

00:04:53.610 --> 00:04:53.810
Yeah, yeah.

00:04:53.810 --> 00:04:54.800
LOGAN URY: What about
through the book?

00:04:54.800 --> 00:04:55.170
Through the experiment?

00:04:55.170 --> 00:04:56.711
GRETCHEN RUBIN: Oh,
through the book.

00:04:56.711 --> 00:04:57.670
Through the book.

00:04:57.670 --> 00:04:58.270
Oh, my gosh.

00:04:58.270 --> 00:04:59.460
There were so many things.

00:04:59.460 --> 00:05:02.530
I mean, there were
a lot of things.

00:05:02.530 --> 00:05:04.720
And if I keep working on this.

00:05:04.720 --> 00:05:07.180
Which is I have a very-- we
were talking about this--

00:05:07.180 --> 00:05:08.854
I have an intense personality.

00:05:08.854 --> 00:05:10.020
I have kind of a short fuse.

00:05:10.020 --> 00:05:13.000
And so a lot of habits and
resolutions and everything

00:05:13.000 --> 00:05:13.930
that I've done.

00:05:13.930 --> 00:05:15.430
Everything from
going to bed on time

00:05:15.430 --> 00:05:18.492
to trying to under
react to problems.

00:05:18.492 --> 00:05:19.950
I mean, a million
different things.

00:05:19.950 --> 00:05:22.040
Trying to just
stay calm and light

00:05:22.040 --> 00:05:24.420
hearted and have
a sense of humor.

00:05:24.420 --> 00:05:30.185
I mean, not take it up to 11
like an opera star every time

00:05:30.185 --> 00:05:31.060
something goes wrong.

00:05:31.060 --> 00:05:32.810
LOGAN URY: And what are
some of the easy things

00:05:32.810 --> 00:05:34.710
that people in this
room or people watching

00:05:34.710 --> 00:05:36.330
could do to be happier?

00:05:36.330 --> 00:05:38.720
GRETCHEN RUBIN:
Get enough sleep.

00:05:38.720 --> 00:05:41.120
How many people here regularly
get seven hours of sleep

00:05:41.120 --> 00:05:42.960
a night?

00:05:42.960 --> 00:05:43.920
OK, that's pretty good.

00:05:43.920 --> 00:05:44.930
That's pretty good.

00:05:44.930 --> 00:05:45.900
AUDIENCE: Liars.

00:05:45.900 --> 00:05:46.385
GRETCHEN RUBIN: Huh?

00:05:46.385 --> 00:05:46.870
AUDIENCE: Liars.

00:05:46.870 --> 00:05:47.745
GRETCHEN RUBIN: Yeah.

00:05:47.745 --> 00:05:48.325
[LAUGHTER]

00:05:48.325 --> 00:05:49.491
GRETCHEN RUBIN: Yeah, liars.

00:05:49.491 --> 00:05:53.074
How many people here
regularly use a snooze alarm?

00:05:53.074 --> 00:05:54.490
Oh, it's an
instrument of torture!

00:05:57.000 --> 00:05:58.342
Well, and then relationships.

00:05:58.342 --> 00:06:00.300
Really when you look at
people who are happier,

00:06:00.300 --> 00:06:03.660
they're the ones that have
deep, meaningful relationships.

00:06:03.660 --> 00:06:05.850
To be happy, we really
need relationships.

00:06:05.850 --> 00:06:08.680
And so anything that you can do
to broaden your relationships

00:06:08.680 --> 00:06:10.510
or deepen your
relationship is something

00:06:10.510 --> 00:06:13.090
that's likely to have
a big happiness payoff.

00:06:13.090 --> 00:06:15.030
I'm a big fan myself
of joining groups

00:06:15.030 --> 00:06:17.860
because I think groups
are a great way to stay

00:06:17.860 --> 00:06:20.980
in touch with a lot of people.

00:06:20.980 --> 00:06:22.542
So those are some of the things.

00:06:22.542 --> 00:06:25.000
LOGAN URY: So transitioning
from "Happiness" to your newest

00:06:25.000 --> 00:06:27.529
book, what role do habits
play in contributing

00:06:27.529 --> 00:06:28.445
to people's happiness?

00:06:28.445 --> 00:06:30.340
GRETCHEN RUBIN: Well,
it's interesting.

00:06:30.340 --> 00:06:32.810
Research suggests that
about 40% of everyday life

00:06:32.810 --> 00:06:34.470
is governed by habits.

00:06:34.470 --> 00:06:38.180
And so habits are the invisible
architecture of everyday life.

00:06:38.180 --> 00:06:39.870
If you have habits
that work for you,

00:06:39.870 --> 00:06:42.015
you're much more likely
to be happier, healthier,

00:06:42.015 --> 00:06:42.937
and more productive.

00:06:42.937 --> 00:06:44.770
If you have habits that
do not work for you,

00:06:44.770 --> 00:06:46.680
that is going to be
much more difficult.

00:06:46.680 --> 00:06:49.660
And I got drawn into
the subject of habits

00:06:49.660 --> 00:06:53.150
from "Happiness" because I
was researching and thinking

00:06:53.150 --> 00:06:56.220
and talking to people
about happiness so much.

00:06:56.220 --> 00:06:58.700
And very often, I
noticed a pattern that

00:06:58.700 --> 00:07:01.230
was when people would talk
about either a big gain

00:07:01.230 --> 00:07:04.440
that they had experienced
or more often,

00:07:04.440 --> 00:07:07.870
a challenge that they kept
facing about happiness,

00:07:07.870 --> 00:07:10.990
it was something that to me at
its core looked like a habit

00:07:10.990 --> 00:07:12.810
problem.

00:07:12.810 --> 00:07:16.490
And so I became
increasingly interested

00:07:16.490 --> 00:07:19.252
in this question
of why do people

00:07:19.252 --> 00:07:20.710
have trouble forming
certain habits

00:07:20.710 --> 00:07:23.000
if they say they want them?

00:07:23.000 --> 00:07:27.320
And sometimes they can form
them, and why can they?

00:07:27.320 --> 00:07:29.607
And then sometimes
they can't, and trying

00:07:29.607 --> 00:07:30.940
to understand what was going on.

00:07:30.940 --> 00:07:32.730
LOGAN URY: So what do
you say if someone says,

00:07:32.730 --> 00:07:34.050
oh, that seems so exhausting?

00:07:34.050 --> 00:07:36.310
Or it's going to take away
the spontaneity in my life?

00:07:36.310 --> 00:07:38.040
GRETCHEN RUBIN: Well, this
is the thing about habits.

00:07:38.040 --> 00:07:40.040
There's good things about
habits and bad things.

00:07:40.040 --> 00:07:42.080
So the good things about
habits is that they

00:07:42.080 --> 00:07:43.640
are freeing and energizing.

00:07:43.640 --> 00:07:46.410
Because when
something's a habit,

00:07:46.410 --> 00:07:47.970
we don't have to
use decision making

00:07:47.970 --> 00:07:49.553
and we don't have
to use self control.

00:07:49.553 --> 00:07:51.330
So I don't decide to
get up at 6:00 AM.

00:07:51.330 --> 00:07:53.090
I don't decide whether
to skip dessert.

00:07:53.090 --> 00:07:54.690
I'm not using my willpower.

00:07:54.690 --> 00:07:55.310
I just don't.

00:07:55.310 --> 00:07:57.747
I made that decision long ago.

00:07:57.747 --> 00:08:00.080
People sometimes say, I want
to go through my day making

00:08:00.080 --> 00:08:01.150
healthy choices.

00:08:01.150 --> 00:08:02.600
I'm like, no you don't!

00:08:02.600 --> 00:08:05.475
Because if you're trying to
make a lot of healthy choices,

00:08:05.475 --> 00:08:06.850
a lot of the time
you're probably

00:08:06.850 --> 00:08:08.141
going to make the wrong choice.

00:08:08.141 --> 00:08:11.202
You want to choose once, make it
a habit, put it on auto pilot.

00:08:11.202 --> 00:08:12.660
And then that just
is going to run.

00:08:12.660 --> 00:08:13.970
And you don't have to
use decision making,

00:08:13.970 --> 00:08:15.430
you don't have to
use self control.

00:08:15.430 --> 00:08:18.930
However, the downside of
habits is that they speed time

00:08:18.930 --> 00:08:20.380
and they deaden.

00:08:20.380 --> 00:08:22.440
So you know, your
first month on a job

00:08:22.440 --> 00:08:24.320
lasts longer than your
fifth year on a job.

00:08:24.320 --> 00:08:27.000
Because everything speeds
up when it's on a habit.

00:08:27.000 --> 00:08:31.094
And also your response
to a situation

00:08:31.094 --> 00:08:32.260
is going to be less intense.

00:08:32.260 --> 00:08:33.980
So if you're doing something
for the first time,

00:08:33.980 --> 00:08:36.409
it's this spontaneous thing,
it's going to be more intense.

00:08:36.409 --> 00:08:38.210
Whereas if it's something
that you're doing every day,

00:08:38.210 --> 00:08:39.309
is going to be deadened.

00:08:39.309 --> 00:08:40.610
But this can be good too.

00:08:40.610 --> 00:08:43.490
You deaden pleasure, but you
also deaden negative emotions

00:08:43.490 --> 00:08:44.350
like anxiety.

00:08:44.350 --> 00:08:46.540
If there's something
that makes you anxious,

00:08:46.540 --> 00:08:48.560
probably the more you
do it, the less anxious

00:08:48.560 --> 00:08:50.430
you're going to feel.

00:08:50.430 --> 00:08:52.680
I heard a guy, an expert
on anxiety, talking.

00:08:52.680 --> 00:08:54.680
And a woman said, well,
I get very, very anxious

00:08:54.680 --> 00:08:56.240
every I have to
get off a ski lift.

00:08:56.240 --> 00:08:58.340
And he said, strangely,
it's because you

00:08:58.340 --> 00:09:00.640
don't get off ski lifts enough.

00:09:00.640 --> 00:09:03.640
If you got off a ski
lift three times a day,

00:09:03.640 --> 00:09:07.220
you would be in the habit of
it and your anxiety would drop.

00:09:07.220 --> 00:09:11.030
But it's just novel enough that
you can have this big stress

00:09:11.030 --> 00:09:11.530
reaction.

00:09:11.530 --> 00:09:14.120
So the deadening can be helpful.

00:09:14.120 --> 00:09:16.220
But often we
experience it as oh, I

00:09:16.220 --> 00:09:18.950
don't enjoy my cup of coffee
in the morning anymore.

00:09:18.950 --> 00:09:20.631
I don't enjoy.

00:09:20.631 --> 00:09:23.130
I'm driving to work, I don't
even see the beautiful scenery.

00:09:23.130 --> 00:09:26.950
Because it just
deadens, speeds away.

00:09:26.950 --> 00:09:27.710
LOGAN URY: Yeah.

00:09:27.710 --> 00:09:29.555
One of my favorite parts of
the book was about abstaining.

00:09:29.555 --> 00:09:30.210
GRETCHEN RUBIN:
[LAUGHS] Oh yeah.

00:09:30.210 --> 00:09:33.376
LOGAN URY: And how you can make
powerful changes in your life

00:09:33.376 --> 00:09:35.000
just by not making
a decision about it.

00:09:35.000 --> 00:09:35.230
GRETCHEN RUBIN: Yeah, yeah.

00:09:35.230 --> 00:09:36.210
LOGAN URY: Or making a
decision about it once.

00:09:36.210 --> 00:09:36.620
GRETCHEN RUBIN: Yes.

00:09:36.620 --> 00:09:37.740
LOGAN URY: Can you talk
a little bit about that?

00:09:37.740 --> 00:09:39.115
GRETCHEN RUBIN:
Yeah, abstaining.

00:09:39.115 --> 00:09:42.760
OK, so I have 21
strategies in the book.

00:09:42.760 --> 00:09:44.650
And don't feel like
oh my gosh, 21!

00:09:44.650 --> 00:09:45.410
It's too many.

00:09:45.410 --> 00:09:45.910
It's good.

00:09:45.910 --> 00:09:48.150
You can have a lot to
pick and choose from.

00:09:48.150 --> 00:09:50.070
And the strategy of
abstaining is interesting

00:09:50.070 --> 00:09:52.340
because it's a strategy
that works extremely

00:09:52.340 --> 00:09:54.650
well for some
people and does not

00:09:54.650 --> 00:09:56.090
work at all for other people.

00:09:56.090 --> 00:09:57.756
So it's very important
to know if you're

00:09:57.756 --> 00:10:00.240
an abstainer or a moderator.

00:10:00.240 --> 00:10:06.160
For abstainers, it's easier
to do something not at all.

00:10:06.160 --> 00:10:09.980
It's easier to give
it up altogether.

00:10:09.980 --> 00:10:13.850
I can have no Thin Mints,
and I can have 10 Thin Mints.

00:10:13.850 --> 00:10:16.060
But I cannot have
two Thin Mints.

00:10:16.060 --> 00:10:18.220
It's easier to have none.

00:10:18.220 --> 00:10:20.020
[LAUGHTER]

00:10:20.020 --> 00:10:22.542
Once something's off the
table, it just goes away.

00:10:22.542 --> 00:10:23.500
I'm not bothered by it.

00:10:23.500 --> 00:10:25.249
But once I start, I
have trouble stopping.

00:10:25.249 --> 00:10:26.306
It's all or nothing.

00:10:26.306 --> 00:10:28.180
And then there are people
who are moderators.

00:10:28.180 --> 00:10:30.740
And moderators get
panicky if they're told

00:10:30.740 --> 00:10:32.396
they can't have something ever.

00:10:32.396 --> 00:10:34.270
They need to know they
can have it sometimes.

00:10:34.270 --> 00:10:39.464
They can have it occasionally.

00:10:39.464 --> 00:10:42.479
And one of the things
that many moderators will

00:10:42.479 --> 00:10:44.770
do-- this was a pattern that
puzzled me for the longest

00:10:44.770 --> 00:10:47.710
time-- is they will keep a bar
of fine chocolate squirreled

00:10:47.710 --> 00:10:48.840
away somewhere.

00:10:48.840 --> 00:10:52.050
And once a day, they
will eat one square

00:10:52.050 --> 00:10:53.300
of that bar of fine chocolate.

00:10:53.300 --> 00:10:57.402
Now my whole day would be like,
a square now, a square later.

00:10:57.402 --> 00:10:58.110
It's my birthday.

00:10:58.110 --> 00:10:58.950
I'm on vacation.

00:10:58.950 --> 00:11:00.890
I was so good, I'll
eat the whole thing,

00:11:00.890 --> 00:11:02.389
I'm not going to
eat anything today.

00:11:02.389 --> 00:11:04.780
So you know, I
would eat that bar.

00:11:04.780 --> 00:11:07.290
But a moderator likes to
have just a little bit.

00:11:07.290 --> 00:11:10.360
And so it's really
important to know

00:11:10.360 --> 00:11:12.295
whether abstaining works
for you or moderating

00:11:12.295 --> 00:11:13.170
works better for you.

00:11:13.170 --> 00:11:15.253
So how many people here,
hearing this description,

00:11:15.253 --> 00:11:16.790
think that they're abstainers?

00:11:16.790 --> 00:11:19.010
How many people think
they're moderators?

00:11:19.010 --> 00:11:21.040
OK, so now you see the
point of conflict, right?

00:11:21.040 --> 00:11:22.499
Because the moderator
is like, well

00:11:22.499 --> 00:11:23.998
let's just buy a
carton of ice cream

00:11:23.998 --> 00:11:25.450
and keep it in the freezer.

00:11:25.450 --> 00:11:27.530
And you can just learn
to control yourself.

00:11:27.530 --> 00:11:30.024
And the abstainer's like, I'm
gonna eat the whole thing!

00:11:30.024 --> 00:11:31.190
Don't bring it in the house!

00:11:31.190 --> 00:11:32.000
So it's hard.

00:11:32.000 --> 00:11:34.560
But this is something
that works also

00:11:34.560 --> 00:11:36.360
for any kind of
strong temptation.

00:11:36.360 --> 00:11:39.262
And as I imagine you
guys are well aware,

00:11:39.262 --> 00:11:41.720
it's something that some people
have to do with technology.

00:11:41.720 --> 00:11:44.960
My sister cannot play a
little bit of Candy Crush.

00:11:44.960 --> 00:11:47.810
She had to delete it
from all of her devices.

00:11:47.810 --> 00:11:51.362
So sometimes when people can't
do something a little bit,

00:11:51.362 --> 00:11:52.820
they have to give
it up altogether.

00:11:52.820 --> 00:11:56.530
And that sounds harder because
it sounds more extreme and more

00:11:56.530 --> 00:11:58.020
rigid and more demanding.

00:11:58.020 --> 00:12:00.900
But if you are an
abstainer, it's easier.

00:12:00.900 --> 00:12:02.530
It's the lazy way.

00:12:02.530 --> 00:12:04.820
It's easy to give
something up altogether.

00:12:04.820 --> 00:12:07.250
It's much, much,
much harder to try

00:12:07.250 --> 00:12:10.814
to be moderate if you are
the abstainer personality.

00:12:10.814 --> 00:12:12.730
LOGAN URY: So one thing
I really found helpful

00:12:12.730 --> 00:12:14.810
in the book is understanding
to change our habits,

00:12:14.810 --> 00:12:15.915
we must figure out ourselves.

00:12:15.915 --> 00:12:16.580
GRETCHEN RUBIN:
Yeah, yeah, yeah.

00:12:16.580 --> 00:12:18.530
LOGAN URY: And I think a
lot of people in this room

00:12:18.530 --> 00:12:20.330
read your books and they
follow your blog because they

00:12:20.330 --> 00:12:21.740
do want to hack their
lives and improve.

00:12:21.740 --> 00:12:22.510
GRETCHEN RUBIN:
Yeah, yeah, yeah.

00:12:22.510 --> 00:12:23.470
LOGAN URY: Maybe you
could talk a little bit

00:12:23.470 --> 00:12:24.330
about the four tendencies.

00:12:24.330 --> 00:12:24.620
GRETCHEN RUBIN: Oh.

00:12:24.620 --> 00:12:26.650
LOGAN URY: And how that's
helped people make habits.

00:12:26.650 --> 00:12:27.350
GRETCHEN RUBIN: OK.

00:12:27.350 --> 00:12:28.850
So of everything
in the book, I have

00:12:28.850 --> 00:12:31.350
to say this is the thing
that is the most original.

00:12:31.350 --> 00:12:33.600
It was definitely the most
intellectually challenging.

00:12:33.600 --> 00:12:36.610
It took me months
and months and months

00:12:36.610 --> 00:12:39.400
of deep pondering to come
up with the four tendencies.

00:12:39.400 --> 00:12:41.234
So I'm going to outline
the four tendencies,

00:12:41.234 --> 00:12:43.775
and then I'm going to go through
and ask you raise your hand.

00:12:43.775 --> 00:12:45.300
Because whenever
I speak, I'm very

00:12:45.300 --> 00:12:46.966
curious to see what
the distribution is.

00:12:49.972 --> 00:12:51.680
And it starts out
sounding really boring.

00:12:51.680 --> 00:12:53.346
So just hang in there
with me, because I

00:12:53.346 --> 00:12:54.550
promise there's payoff.

00:12:54.550 --> 00:12:56.770
But it really does sound
boring when I start.

00:12:56.770 --> 00:12:59.050
So this has to do
with how you respond

00:12:59.050 --> 00:13:00.800
to the idea of an expectation.

00:13:00.800 --> 00:13:03.650
So there are outer expectations,
like a work deadline,

00:13:03.650 --> 00:13:07.017
or request from a spouse,
or a traffic regulation.

00:13:07.017 --> 00:13:08.600
And then there are
inner expectations,

00:13:08.600 --> 00:13:11.900
which is like your own desire
to keep a New Year's resolution,

00:13:11.900 --> 00:13:15.720
or your own desire to
get back into meditation.

00:13:15.720 --> 00:13:18.670
The first category of
people are upholders.

00:13:18.670 --> 00:13:21.880
Upholders respond readily to
outer and inner expectations

00:13:21.880 --> 00:13:22.420
alike.

00:13:22.420 --> 00:13:24.300
So they meet a work deadline
without too much trouble.

00:13:24.300 --> 00:13:25.674
They keep a New
Year's resolution

00:13:25.674 --> 00:13:26.590
without much trouble.

00:13:26.590 --> 00:13:30.750
It's very important to them
to meet external expectations,

00:13:30.750 --> 00:13:33.010
but it's just as important
or more important

00:13:33.010 --> 00:13:36.330
for them to meet their
expectations for themselves.

00:13:36.330 --> 00:13:37.820
Next, questioners.

00:13:37.820 --> 00:13:39.930
Questioners question
all expectations.

00:13:39.930 --> 00:13:42.980
They'll do it if it
makes sense to them.

00:13:42.980 --> 00:13:45.120
They hate anything
arbitrary or irrational.

00:13:45.120 --> 00:13:47.780
They want to know why
am I listening to you?

00:13:47.780 --> 00:13:50.980
They want reasons and
justification, sometimes

00:13:50.980 --> 00:13:52.440
too much.

00:13:52.440 --> 00:13:54.280
And so in a way,
they make everything

00:13:54.280 --> 00:13:56.890
an inner expectation,
because they'll do it

00:13:56.890 --> 00:13:58.650
if it passes muster with them.

00:13:58.650 --> 00:14:00.660
So it's an inner expectation.

00:14:00.660 --> 00:14:02.070
Then obligers.

00:14:02.070 --> 00:14:04.311
Obligers readily meet
outer expectations,

00:14:04.311 --> 00:14:06.310
but they have trouble
meeting their expectations

00:14:06.310 --> 00:14:06.980
for themselves.

00:14:06.980 --> 00:14:08.320
So for instance--
and I talk about this

00:14:08.320 --> 00:14:09.695
at the very
beginning of the book

00:14:09.695 --> 00:14:11.860
because it was a very
clarifying moment for me--

00:14:11.860 --> 00:14:14.326
a friend of mine said,
why can't I exercise?

00:14:14.326 --> 00:14:15.950
In high school, I
was on the track team

00:14:15.950 --> 00:14:17.570
and I never missed
track practice.

00:14:17.570 --> 00:14:19.060
But I can't go running now.

00:14:19.060 --> 00:14:20.096
Why?

00:14:20.096 --> 00:14:21.220
Because she was an obliger.

00:14:21.220 --> 00:14:23.340
When there was a team,
when there was a coach,

00:14:23.340 --> 00:14:25.190
she could meet the
external expectation.

00:14:25.190 --> 00:14:26.680
But she can't go
running on her own

00:14:26.680 --> 00:14:28.520
because that's just
an inner expectation,

00:14:28.520 --> 00:14:30.400
and so that's harder to meet.

00:14:30.400 --> 00:14:32.030
And then finally, rebels.

00:14:32.030 --> 00:14:34.364
Rebels resist all expectations,
outer and inner alike.

00:14:34.364 --> 00:14:36.280
They want to do what
they want to do when they

00:14:36.280 --> 00:14:37.900
want to do it in their own way.

00:14:37.900 --> 00:14:39.640
If you ask or tell
them to do something,

00:14:39.640 --> 00:14:41.499
they're very likely
to do the opposite.

00:14:41.499 --> 00:14:43.540
And they sometimes become
frustrated because they

00:14:43.540 --> 00:14:46.119
don't even want to tell
themselves what do.

00:14:46.119 --> 00:14:47.660
So they resist outer
and inner alike.

00:14:47.660 --> 00:14:50.000
OK, upholders?

00:14:50.000 --> 00:14:51.920
Readily meets outer
and inner expectation.

00:14:51.920 --> 00:14:52.755
Upholder.

00:14:52.755 --> 00:14:55.100
Yeah, that's
definitely my tendency.

00:14:55.100 --> 00:14:55.960
Next, questioners.

00:14:55.960 --> 00:14:58.760
Questioners question
all expectations.

00:14:58.760 --> 00:15:00.450
Yeah, OK.

00:15:00.450 --> 00:15:01.160
Next, obligers.

00:15:01.160 --> 00:15:04.260
Obligers readily meet outer,
struggle to keep inner.

00:15:04.260 --> 00:15:05.140
And then rebels.

00:15:05.140 --> 00:15:08.924
Rebels resist both
outer and inner alike.

00:15:08.924 --> 00:15:10.327
OK.

00:15:10.327 --> 00:15:12.910
LOGAN URY: My theory was there
would be more rebels at Google.

00:15:12.910 --> 00:15:13.740
GRETCHEN RUBIN: Ah.

00:15:13.740 --> 00:15:16.976
Well, I've spoken to
groups that had no rebels.

00:15:16.976 --> 00:15:20.190
LOGAN URY: Any themes among
groups with no rebels?

00:15:20.190 --> 00:15:22.310
GRETCHEN RUBIN: The
theme you would expect.

00:15:22.310 --> 00:15:26.080
They tend to be places where
there's a super high emphasis

00:15:26.080 --> 00:15:27.740
on keeping rules.

00:15:27.740 --> 00:15:30.670
Strangely, the group that
had the highest percentage

00:15:30.670 --> 00:15:32.990
of rebels-- well, I should
start by saying rebel

00:15:32.990 --> 00:15:35.070
is by far the smallest category.

00:15:35.070 --> 00:15:37.160
Very, very few
people are rebels.

00:15:37.160 --> 00:15:40.240
But what was surprising to
me was that very few people

00:15:40.240 --> 00:15:41.516
are upholders.

00:15:41.516 --> 00:15:42.640
It's a very small category.

00:15:42.640 --> 00:15:43.864
These are the extremes.

00:15:43.864 --> 00:15:45.530
When I was starting
this book, I did not

00:15:45.530 --> 00:15:48.910
realize that I was part of
the freaky fringe, but I am.

00:15:48.910 --> 00:15:51.440
But the group that I spoke to
that had by far the highest

00:15:51.440 --> 00:15:52.980
percentage of
rebels-- it was still

00:15:52.980 --> 00:15:54.360
on absolute terms
a small number,

00:15:54.360 --> 00:15:56.020
but in terms of the number
of hands that went up,

00:15:56.020 --> 00:15:57.840
I was astounded-- was
when I spoke to group

00:15:57.840 --> 00:15:59.220
of Christian ministers.

00:15:59.220 --> 00:16:00.310
[LAUGHTER]

00:16:00.310 --> 00:16:02.150
And there's a whole
thing that I won't

00:16:02.150 --> 00:16:04.980
go into about why that
is, about rebels are often

00:16:04.980 --> 00:16:09.250
attracted strangely to
areas of high regulation.

00:16:09.250 --> 00:16:12.970
But by far, most people are
questioners or obligers.

00:16:12.970 --> 00:16:16.700
I think obligers is
in the slight lead.

00:16:16.700 --> 00:16:19.170
There's a quiz on my site
if you want to take it.

00:16:19.170 --> 00:16:23.810
117,000 people
now have taken it.

00:16:23.810 --> 00:16:27.390
But most people are questioners
or obligers, overwhelmingly.

00:16:27.390 --> 00:16:30.150
And I couldn't totally
get a sense of it,

00:16:30.150 --> 00:16:32.460
but I think that was pretty
much what we saw here.

00:16:32.712 --> 00:16:34.420
