00:17:57.540 --> 00:17:59.210
that if you even had
10 loose minutes,

00:17:59.210 --> 00:18:02.720
that you could sit down and
get something done because it's

00:18:02.720 --> 00:18:04.000
just in your mind so vividly.

00:18:06.700 --> 00:18:10.310
And so I think that's
part of what works for me.

00:18:10.310 --> 00:18:11.831
But I have to say
though, I always

00:18:11.831 --> 00:18:13.830
thought that was a standard
thing that everybody

00:18:13.830 --> 00:18:15.913
should do in order to be
productive and efficient.

00:18:15.913 --> 00:18:19.530
But one of the things I
learned from the book,

00:18:19.530 --> 00:18:21.600
one chapter is on the
strategy of distinctions,

00:18:21.600 --> 00:18:23.877
which is understanding
how people are alike

00:18:23.877 --> 00:18:24.960
and how they're different.

00:18:24.960 --> 00:18:26.850
Because a lot of times,
I assume everybody

00:18:26.850 --> 00:18:29.099
would do better if they
worked a little bit every day.

00:18:29.099 --> 00:18:30.730
Because isn't that the best way?

00:18:30.730 --> 00:18:32.890
No, it's the best way for me.

00:18:32.890 --> 00:18:34.650
So there's marathoners
like me who like

00:18:34.650 --> 00:18:36.287
to do a little bit steadily.

00:18:36.287 --> 00:18:38.620
We feel like that helps our
creativity and productivity.

00:18:38.620 --> 00:18:39.906
But then there are sprinters.

00:18:39.906 --> 00:18:41.780
Sprinters like the
adrenalin of the deadline.

00:18:41.780 --> 00:18:44.245
They like to do everything
up against that end.

00:18:44.245 --> 00:18:45.870
They feel like that's
what crystallizes

00:18:45.870 --> 00:18:47.760
their thoughts, that's when
they're most productive.

00:18:47.760 --> 00:18:49.843
And if they start too
early, they kind of burn out

00:18:49.843 --> 00:18:52.500
and waste time and the
whole thing stretches out.

00:18:52.500 --> 00:18:54.400
And it was a real
revelation because I just

00:18:54.400 --> 00:18:57.130
thought that they were
being irresponsible.

00:18:57.130 --> 00:18:59.724
Why would you possibly
wait like that?

00:18:59.724 --> 00:19:02.140
But then as I would really
talk to people about their work

00:19:02.140 --> 00:19:04.427
habits, that's really
how they worked best.

00:19:04.427 --> 00:19:06.010
And there's no right
way or wrong way.

00:19:06.010 --> 00:19:07.715
But you can imagine
in a team situation,

00:19:07.715 --> 00:19:08.780
it can be really hard.

00:19:08.780 --> 00:19:10.640
And I've heard from a
lot of people saying,

00:19:10.640 --> 00:19:11.770
oh well, I worked
in this law firm

00:19:11.770 --> 00:19:13.270
for this partner
who was a sprinter.

00:19:13.270 --> 00:19:15.690
And I couldn't work like that.

00:19:15.690 --> 00:19:17.280
It seemed crazy to me.

00:19:17.280 --> 00:19:21.410
Or I was talking to a guy
who led a software team.

00:19:21.410 --> 00:19:23.796
And he's like, oh, that's
when teams come together.

00:19:23.796 --> 00:19:25.170
That's when the
great ideas flow.

00:19:25.170 --> 00:19:26.210
And I was like, no.

00:19:26.210 --> 00:19:27.090
For you.

00:19:27.090 --> 00:19:28.350
I couldn't work like that.

00:19:28.350 --> 00:19:31.610
So it's understanding that
maybe people have different work

00:19:31.610 --> 00:19:33.330
styles, work paces.

00:19:33.330 --> 00:19:35.780
And so if you talk
about what are the best

00:19:35.780 --> 00:19:38.406
habits for productivity,
should you do it first thing

00:19:38.406 --> 00:19:39.030
in the morning?

00:19:39.030 --> 00:19:40.863
Not if you're a night
person, because that's

00:19:40.863 --> 00:19:43.350
when probably at your foggiest.

00:19:43.350 --> 00:19:45.080
They might do it
at eight o'clock

00:19:45.080 --> 00:19:48.130
at night, which is when
I can barely speak.

00:19:48.130 --> 00:19:50.550
So it's hard to say,
because it's really

00:19:50.550 --> 00:19:51.950
about that individual fit.

00:19:51.950 --> 00:19:52.680
LOGAN URY: That's
what I found really

00:19:52.680 --> 00:19:53.960
empowering about the
book, was saying,

00:19:53.960 --> 00:19:55.040
oh that didn't work for me.

00:19:55.040 --> 00:19:55.280
GRETCHEN RUBIN: Yeah.

00:19:55.280 --> 00:19:56.280
LOGAN URY: Because I'm this
different type of person.

00:19:56.280 --> 00:19:56.630
GRETCHEN RUBIN:
Yeah, yeah, yeah.

00:19:56.630 --> 00:19:57.615
LOGAN URY: But I am
a morning person.

00:19:57.615 --> 00:19:57.880
GRETCHEN RUBIN: Yeah.

00:19:57.880 --> 00:19:59.760
LOGAN URY: So I've started
making habits based on that.

00:19:59.760 --> 00:20:00.910
GRETCHEN RUBIN: No, because
I think a lot of people

00:20:00.910 --> 00:20:02.480
get discouraged because
something doesn't work.

00:20:02.480 --> 00:20:04.490
And on paper, it sounds
like a great idea.

00:20:04.490 --> 00:20:07.224
And then you're like well, maybe
it's just not suitable for you.

00:20:07.224 --> 00:20:07.890
LOGAN URY: Yeah.

00:20:07.890 --> 00:20:09.120
So what would you
say to managers

00:20:09.120 --> 00:20:10.590
in the room who are
trying to figure out

00:20:10.590 --> 00:20:12.580
how to make their team
happiest and most productive?

00:20:12.580 --> 00:20:13.490
GRETCHEN RUBIN: Well,
I think the thing to do

00:20:13.490 --> 00:20:16.890
is to really look at what is the
reality of how people behave?

00:20:16.890 --> 00:20:20.770
And not say well, this
is the best way to do it.

00:20:20.770 --> 00:20:25.455
Because maybe you have to
work with different types.

00:20:26.420 --> 00:20:28.250
Let's say that you're
managing obligers.

00:20:28.250 --> 00:20:29.630
Well, then you
need to have forms

00:20:29.630 --> 00:20:30.760
of external accountability.

00:20:30.760 --> 00:20:33.300
You can't be like well, will
you just go do this and tell me

00:20:33.300 --> 00:20:33.910
when you're done?

00:20:33.910 --> 00:20:35.210
Because it just
might never get done.

00:20:35.210 --> 00:20:36.377
You need to have a deadline.

00:20:36.377 --> 00:20:38.376
You need to have a sense
of supervision, a sense

00:20:38.376 --> 00:20:39.950
that there's external
accountability.

00:20:39.950 --> 00:20:41.204
But obligers often burn out.

00:20:41.204 --> 00:20:41.870
LOGAN URY: Yeah.

00:20:41.870 --> 00:20:43.495
GRETCHEN RUBIN: So
if you're a manager,

00:20:43.495 --> 00:20:47.130
you need to encourage your
obligers to take time.

00:20:47.130 --> 00:20:51.390
To not push themselves
too hard, because it's

00:20:51.390 --> 00:20:54.160
going to be hard for them not
to meet an external expectation

00:20:54.160 --> 00:20:56.285
even when they're really
at the end of their ropes.

00:20:56.285 --> 00:20:57.760
So you have to
find ways to force

00:20:57.760 --> 00:21:01.620
them to relax and to say no.

00:21:01.620 --> 00:21:02.160
Questioners.

00:21:02.160 --> 00:21:04.712
A lot of times in teams,
there's one person who's like,

00:21:04.712 --> 00:21:05.920
why are we doing it this way?

00:21:05.920 --> 00:21:06.760
Why are we doing it at all?

00:21:06.760 --> 00:21:07.945
Why am I listening to you?

00:21:07.945 --> 00:21:08.820
Is this the best way?

00:21:08.820 --> 00:21:09.859
Is there another way?

00:21:09.859 --> 00:21:10.900
Did you think about this?

00:21:10.900 --> 00:21:12.460
Maybe we should
interview somebody else?

00:21:12.460 --> 00:21:14.126
And everybody's like,
we've all decided!

00:21:14.126 --> 00:21:15.100
Let it go!

00:21:15.100 --> 00:21:16.455
[LAUGHTER]

00:21:16.455 --> 00:21:18.830
And questioners sometimes get
frustrated with themselves.

00:21:18.830 --> 00:21:18.890
LOGAN URY: Yeah.

00:21:18.890 --> 00:21:20.240
GRETCHEN RUBIN: Like
a friend of mine said,

00:21:20.240 --> 00:21:21.710
I have analysis paralysis.

00:21:21.710 --> 00:21:24.040
I always want just a little
bit more information.

00:21:24.040 --> 00:21:26.690
I don't like acting without
perfect information.

00:21:26.690 --> 00:21:29.395
But the fact is, often we
don't have perfect information

00:21:29.395 --> 00:21:31.640
and we can't wait for
perfect information.

00:21:31.640 --> 00:21:33.480
And so part of it
with questioners

00:21:33.480 --> 00:21:35.154
is giving them
the justification,

00:21:35.154 --> 00:21:36.570
taking them through
the rationale.

00:21:36.570 --> 00:21:39.090
And then also helping
them to say we're

00:21:39.090 --> 00:21:41.290
going to interview five
people, but not 50 people.

00:21:41.290 --> 00:21:43.570
We're going to look at this
for this amount of time

00:21:43.570 --> 00:21:44.986
and to this degree,
and then we're

00:21:44.986 --> 00:21:47.524
going to move on so
that it's bounded.

00:21:47.524 --> 00:21:48.190
LOGAN URY: Yeah.

00:21:48.190 --> 00:21:49.490
GRETCHEN RUBIN: So
there's a lot of ways

00:21:49.490 --> 00:21:50.820
that it can come up in teams.

00:21:50.820 --> 00:21:51.180
LOGAN URY: Yeah.

00:21:51.180 --> 00:21:53.260
I really like the part of
your book how you name things.

00:21:53.260 --> 00:21:55.011
Because I think it's
also very empowering.

00:21:55.011 --> 00:21:57.343
Because then I can see somebody
saying to their manager,

00:21:57.343 --> 00:21:57.980
I'm an obliger.

00:21:57.980 --> 00:21:58.180
GRETCHEN RUBIN:
Yeah, yeah, yeah.

00:21:58.180 --> 00:21:59.725
LOGAN URY: So I need you to
create more accountability.

00:21:59.725 --> 00:22:00.050
GRETCHEN RUBIN:
Yeah, yeah, yeah.

00:22:00.050 --> 00:22:00.430
Yes, yes.

00:22:00.430 --> 00:22:02.160
LOGAN URY: And I think
naming things is great.

00:22:02.160 --> 00:22:04.420
Maybe you can talk a little
bit about loophole rejecting?

00:22:04.420 --> 00:22:05.080
GRETCHEN RUBIN: Oh right, right.

00:22:05.080 --> 00:22:07.190
LOGAN URY: That's one of
favorite terms that you coined.

00:22:07.190 --> 00:22:09.250
GRETCHEN RUBIN: So I love
all my 21 strategies.

00:22:09.250 --> 00:22:13.732
But the funniest strategy, and
the one that I was always-- you

00:22:13.732 --> 00:22:16.190
know how you always want to
work on the things that already

00:22:16.190 --> 00:22:17.819
the best?

00:22:17.819 --> 00:22:19.860
I was always tinkering
with the loophole chapter,

00:22:19.860 --> 00:22:20.530
because I love it so much.

00:22:20.530 --> 00:22:22.490
So there's 10
categories of loopholes.

00:22:22.490 --> 00:22:24.690
They are all hilarious
because we are

00:22:24.690 --> 00:22:26.419
such advocates for ourselves.

00:22:26.419 --> 00:22:28.460
So a loophole is something--
you're not mindfully

00:22:28.460 --> 00:22:30.679
making an exception to a
habit, which we can all do.

00:22:30.679 --> 00:22:31.470
We're all grownups.

00:22:31.470 --> 00:22:33.750
We can do whatever we want.

00:22:33.750 --> 00:22:35.956
But a loophole is when in
the heat of the moment,

00:22:35.956 --> 00:22:37.830
it's like a cellphone
searching for a signal.

00:22:37.830 --> 00:22:39.440
You're like, wait a minute!

00:22:39.440 --> 00:22:40.580
I'm off the hook here!

00:22:40.580 --> 00:22:43.624
I forgot, I'm going to
be so good tomorrow,

00:22:43.624 --> 00:22:45.040
it doesn't matter
what I do today.

00:22:45.040 --> 00:22:46.007
All right!

00:22:46.007 --> 00:22:46.840
Or it's my birthday.

00:22:46.840 --> 00:22:47.506
I'm on vacation.

00:22:47.506 --> 00:22:48.870
It's raining.

00:22:48.870 --> 00:22:51.070
I hurt my foot.

00:22:51.070 --> 00:22:54.050
And so there's 10
categories, and they're all

00:22:54.050 --> 00:22:55.080
incredibly popular.

00:22:55.080 --> 00:22:56.340
Everybody has a few favorites.

00:22:56.340 --> 00:22:57.923
My favorite is the
false choice, which

00:22:57.923 --> 00:23:00.890
is I'm too busy
writing to exercise.

00:23:00.890 --> 00:23:03.000
No, really the day
is long enough for me

00:23:03.000 --> 00:23:05.540
to do both those things
most of the time.

00:23:05.540 --> 00:23:11.230
Another very popular one is
the fake self actualization

00:23:11.230 --> 00:23:14.660
loophole, which is when in the
moment, you're like, you know,

00:23:14.660 --> 00:23:15.866
you only live once!

00:23:15.866 --> 00:23:17.490
Life's too short not
to have a brownie!

00:23:17.490 --> 00:23:18.270
LOGAN URY: The YOLO loophole.

00:23:18.270 --> 00:23:18.780
GRETCHEN RUBIN: Yeah,
yeah, yeah, yeah.

00:23:18.780 --> 00:23:19.647
YOLO.

00:23:19.647 --> 00:23:21.480
I have to take advantage
of this opportunity

00:23:21.480 --> 00:23:22.326
or miss out forever.

00:23:22.326 --> 00:23:23.575
I mean, a pumpkin spice latte.

00:23:23.575 --> 00:23:24.360
Who could say no?

00:23:24.360 --> 00:23:26.550
[LAUGHTER]

00:23:26.550 --> 00:23:29.050
So that's fake
self actualization.

00:23:29.050 --> 00:23:31.330
Another one is planning to fail.

00:23:31.330 --> 00:23:34.489
Which is when you very carefully
arrange a set of circumstances

00:23:34.489 --> 00:23:36.530
so that then you're in a
place where no one could

00:23:36.530 --> 00:23:37.890
expect you to resist.

00:23:37.890 --> 00:23:41.700
And my favorite story like this
was told to me by a friend.

00:23:41.700 --> 00:23:44.520
And he had a friend who
had a gambling problem.

00:23:44.520 --> 00:23:47.520
And so he ran into the guy--
he lived in Los Angeles.

00:23:47.520 --> 00:23:49.699
And he ran into the guy
and he said, how you doing?

00:23:49.699 --> 00:23:51.740
And the guy said, I'm not
doing so well because I

00:23:51.740 --> 00:23:52.680
lost a lot of money gambling.

00:23:52.680 --> 00:23:53.690
He said, well, I
thought you weren't

00:23:53.690 --> 00:23:55.055
going to do that anymore.

00:23:55.055 --> 00:23:57.740
And he said, well you
know, I was in Vegas.

00:23:57.740 --> 00:23:59.560
Why were you in Las Vegas?

00:23:59.560 --> 00:24:01.410
Well, I just bought a
new car and I wanted

00:24:01.410 --> 00:24:02.900
to take it for a test drive.

00:24:02.900 --> 00:24:04.750
To Las Vegas!

00:24:04.750 --> 00:24:05.751
That's planning to fail.

00:24:05.751 --> 00:24:06.416
LOGAN URY: Yeah.

00:24:06.416 --> 00:24:08.770
GRETCHEN RUBIN: But one of
the most dangerous loopholes,

00:24:08.770 --> 00:24:12.480
because it's absolutely true
and it works in every situation,

00:24:12.480 --> 00:24:14.570
is the one coin loophole.

00:24:14.570 --> 00:24:16.310
And this comes from
an ancient teaching

00:24:16.310 --> 00:24:22.100
story which says would you say
that one coin makes a man rich?

00:24:22.100 --> 00:24:23.020
You would say no.

00:24:23.020 --> 00:24:24.437
One coin does not
make a man rich.

00:24:24.437 --> 00:24:26.020
But what if you give
him another coin,

00:24:26.020 --> 00:24:27.616
and what if you give
him another coin?

00:24:27.616 --> 00:24:29.990
At some point, you have to
say that a man has become rich

00:24:29.990 --> 00:24:32.250
because one coin made him rich.

00:24:32.250 --> 00:24:35.050
And this is the
thing with habits.

00:24:35.050 --> 00:24:38.280
What is one trip to the
gym going to do for me?

00:24:38.280 --> 00:24:40.809
What's one cupcake?

00:24:40.809 --> 00:24:42.600
Why should I bother to
wear a helmet today?

00:24:42.600 --> 00:24:45.890
What are the chances I'm going
to get an accident today?

00:24:45.890 --> 00:24:47.406
But the only way
you get the benefit

00:24:47.406 --> 00:24:48.780
of a habit, the
only way you form

00:24:48.780 --> 00:24:52.260
a habit is one coin after
one coin after one coin.

00:24:52.260 --> 00:24:56.330
But at any particular
moment, that one-- why

00:24:56.330 --> 00:24:58.290
should I work on my
Ph.D thesis today?

00:24:58.290 --> 00:25:00.070
I'm not going to turn
it in for two years.

00:25:00.070 --> 00:25:01.305
It always works.

00:25:01.305 --> 00:25:03.050
It always works.

00:25:03.050 --> 00:25:06.200
But the fact is that's the
only way we do anything

00:25:06.200 --> 00:25:08.250
is by doing it right now.

00:25:08.250 --> 00:25:11.805
And so people will often
shift between these two

00:25:11.805 --> 00:25:12.680
at their convenience.

00:25:12.680 --> 00:25:14.888
Like it's really important
to me to read to my child,

00:25:14.888 --> 00:25:16.820
but I'm not going
to do it tonight.

00:25:16.820 --> 00:25:19.780
But how are you ever going to
do if you don't do it tonight?

00:25:19.780 --> 00:25:21.480
So it's a really
insidious loophole,

00:25:21.480 --> 00:25:23.700
because it's always accurate.

00:25:23.700 --> 00:25:25.580
But if you really
follow it, then you

00:25:25.580 --> 00:25:27.070
would never do anything.

00:25:27.070 --> 00:25:28.140
But they're all so fun.

00:25:28.140 --> 00:25:29.370
They're all so imaginative.

00:25:29.370 --> 00:25:30.090
LOGAN URY: Yeah.

00:25:30.090 --> 00:25:32.090
One part of your book I
found really interesting

00:25:32.090 --> 00:25:34.290
was how hard it is to start
a habit the second time.

00:25:34.290 --> 00:25:34.590
GRETCHEN RUBIN: Yes!

00:25:34.590 --> 00:25:35.960
LOGAN URY: So you put a lot
of effort in the first time.

00:25:35.960 --> 00:25:36.680
GRETCHEN RUBIN: Weird, yes!

00:25:36.680 --> 00:25:37.660
LOGAN URY: Can you talk
a little bit about that?

00:25:37.660 --> 00:25:39.360
GRETCHEN RUBIN: Yeah, it's
this thing that I noticed.

00:25:39.360 --> 00:25:40.690
Starting over is harder.

00:25:40.690 --> 00:25:40.800
LOGAN URY: Yeah.

00:25:40.800 --> 00:25:43.383
GRETCHEN RUBIN: And many people
would say oh, I did this thing

00:25:43.383 --> 00:25:44.590
and it was not so hard.

00:25:44.590 --> 00:25:46.767
But then for some
reason I stopped,

00:25:46.767 --> 00:25:48.350
and then I had to
start over, and then

00:25:48.350 --> 00:25:50.110
I couldn't do it again.

00:25:50.110 --> 00:25:51.631
And so it's very
important whenever

00:25:51.631 --> 00:25:53.130
you have a good
habit that you don't

00:25:53.130 --> 00:25:56.722
want to allow yourself to stop.

00:25:56.722 --> 00:25:57.930
Let's say you go on vacation.

00:25:57.930 --> 00:26:00.620
You don't want to conceive
that as a stopping, but really

00:26:00.620 --> 00:26:03.220
always have a plan for what
happens on the other side.

00:26:03.220 --> 00:26:06.870
Like maybe I can't do it for
this month, but on this date

00:26:06.870 --> 00:26:08.630
I'm going back to
the gym or I'm going

00:26:08.630 --> 00:26:13.270
to start doing my Spanish
class again or whatever it is.

00:26:13.270 --> 00:26:17.647
And weirdly, a strange stopping
point is reaching a goal.

00:26:17.647 --> 00:26:20.230
You would think reaching a goal
would energize people and help

00:26:20.230 --> 00:26:22.590
them keep their habits.

00:26:22.590 --> 00:26:25.160
But actually hitting a goal
is a kind of finish line.

00:26:25.160 --> 00:26:28.150
You feel like, oh
I've achieved my goal.

00:26:28.150 --> 00:26:30.927
I did a 60 day sugar detox.

00:26:30.927 --> 00:26:32.760
But really if you're
trying to form a habit,

00:26:32.760 --> 00:26:34.590
you want it to keep going.

00:26:34.590 --> 00:26:35.970
So the finish line is dangerous.

00:26:35.970 --> 00:26:37.845
You maybe want to think
of it as a milestone.

00:26:37.845 --> 00:26:40.196
It's an exciting milestone,
but it's not a finish line.

00:26:40.196 --> 00:26:41.180
LOGAN URY: Yeah.

00:26:41.180 --> 00:26:42.490
That resonated a lot with me.

00:26:42.490 --> 00:26:42.690
GRETCHEN RUBIN: Yeah.

00:26:42.690 --> 00:26:44.856
LOGAN URY: So Google products
are immensely popular.

00:26:44.856 --> 00:26:46.954
For example, there's over
500 million Gmail users.

00:26:46.954 --> 00:26:48.370
GRETCHEN RUBIN:
Yeah. [INAUDIBLE].

00:26:48.370 --> 00:26:50.130
LOGAN URY: With this in mind,
and with probably people

00:26:50.130 --> 00:26:52.005
in this room who work
on those products, what

00:26:52.005 --> 00:26:54.144
are some things that Google
could do to help people

00:26:54.144 --> 00:26:56.810
through the insights that you've
had about happiness and habits?

00:26:56.810 --> 00:26:59.120
GRETCHEN RUBIN: Interesting.

00:26:59.120 --> 00:27:01.020
Well, it's always good
to make everything

00:27:01.020 --> 00:27:02.869
that you want to do
to be very convenient

00:27:02.869 --> 00:27:05.285
and anything you don't want
to do to be very inconvenient.

00:27:05.285 --> 00:27:07.065
So I'm trying to think of what--

00:27:07.065 --> 00:27:08.940
LOGAN URY: So there's
YouTube, Gmail, Search.

00:27:08.940 --> 00:27:10.398
GRETCHEN RUBIN:
Oh, maybe you could

00:27:10.398 --> 00:27:13.090
have a thing on your
