It's never feeling
like it's helping.

00:36:02.681 --> 00:36:05.180
And so that's when you want to
say this is not right for me.

00:36:05.180 --> 00:36:07.609
But I also think that you
can design it up front.

00:36:07.609 --> 00:36:09.900
I think if you think about
yourself with the strategies

00:36:09.900 --> 00:36:16.176
that you could try, you can
avoid a lot of false starts

00:36:16.176 --> 00:36:18.800
because you're designing things
in a way that are going to work

00:36:18.800 --> 00:36:20.030
for you from the beginning.

00:36:20.030 --> 00:36:21.530
And a lot of times,
people are like,

00:36:21.530 --> 00:36:23.489
well this is what worked
for Benjamin Franklin.

00:36:23.489 --> 00:36:26.071
Well, it's going to work for you
if you're a lot like Benjamin

00:36:26.071 --> 00:36:27.259
Franklin, but otherwise no.

00:36:27.259 --> 00:36:28.800
And another thing
that's very helpful

00:36:28.800 --> 00:36:31.174
when you're trying to evaluate
what might work for you is

00:36:31.174 --> 00:36:35.340
was there a time in your past
when you had good success?

00:36:35.340 --> 00:36:36.390
Like my friend.

00:36:36.390 --> 00:36:38.650
There was a clue
to her that she had

00:36:38.650 --> 00:36:42.030
no trouble with this habit
when she was on the track team.

00:36:42.030 --> 00:36:44.300
She didn't understand
what the clue was.

00:36:44.300 --> 00:36:45.890
The clue was external
accountability.

00:36:45.890 --> 00:36:47.050
But there was there.

00:36:47.050 --> 00:36:48.883
And I talked to somebody
who was like, well,

00:36:48.883 --> 00:36:50.210
I thought I hated to cook.

00:36:50.210 --> 00:36:51.270
But then when I
thought back on it,

00:36:51.270 --> 00:36:52.630
I realized when I
lived in a group house

00:36:52.630 --> 00:36:55.130
after college I cooked all
the time and I enjoyed it.

00:36:55.130 --> 00:36:57.320
And when I thought about
what was different,

00:36:57.320 --> 00:37:00.470
it's that my roommate
loved to food shop.

00:37:00.470 --> 00:37:03.700
She said, I realized it's
not that I dislike cooking.

00:37:03.700 --> 00:37:05.874
I hate food shopping.

00:37:05.874 --> 00:37:07.290
And so then she
organized her life

00:37:07.290 --> 00:37:08.780
so she didn't do
any food shopping

00:37:08.780 --> 00:37:10.230
and then she was happy to cook.

00:37:10.230 --> 00:37:12.344
So sometimes looking
at times in your past

00:37:12.344 --> 00:37:14.510
and thinking about well,
what were the circumstances

00:37:14.510 --> 00:37:16.344
there that contributed
to it being possible?

00:37:16.344 --> 00:37:18.676
Because a lot of times when
we're trying to form habits,

00:37:18.676 --> 00:37:21.470
there have been times when we
were able to be productive,

00:37:21.470 --> 00:37:24.869
or we were being able
to stick to something.

00:37:24.869 --> 00:37:27.035
But then I think sometimes
we don't think about that

00:37:27.035 --> 00:37:28.425
when we're moving forward.

00:37:28.425 --> 00:37:30.550
AUDIENCE: And you think
that's a core nature thing?

00:37:30.550 --> 00:37:33.610
Not a, when I was 20, I was a
different person than I am now?

00:37:33.610 --> 00:37:36.210
GRETCHEN RUBIN: Well, I think
it's probably a core nature

00:37:36.210 --> 00:37:37.710
thing.

00:37:37.710 --> 00:37:38.722
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:37:38.722 --> 00:37:42.620
AUDIENCE: Is it possible
to help others form habits?

00:37:42.620 --> 00:37:46.760
Especially those who
are trying and failing

00:37:46.760 --> 00:37:48.200
and you want to do something?

00:37:48.200 --> 00:37:49.116
GRETCHEN RUBIN: Right.

00:37:49.116 --> 00:37:50.930
AUDIENCE: Can you
help or does it

00:37:50.930 --> 00:37:54.672
have to come from within
the person him or herself?

00:37:54.672 --> 00:37:56.880
GRETCHEN RUBIN: Well, that's
an interesting question.

00:37:56.880 --> 00:38:00.040
Because if a person
truly doesn't

00:38:00.040 --> 00:38:02.290
want to form a habit then I
think it's very difficult.

00:38:02.290 --> 00:38:05.100
And sometimes people have what
I would call red herring habits,

00:38:05.100 --> 00:38:07.490
where they're making the sounds.

00:38:07.490 --> 00:38:09.080
I really should exercise.

00:38:09.080 --> 00:38:10.350
You're telling me to exercise.

00:38:10.350 --> 00:38:10.840
Yeah, you're right.

00:38:10.840 --> 00:38:11.920
I should really exercise.

00:38:11.920 --> 00:38:13.220
They have no intention
of exercising.

00:38:13.220 --> 00:38:15.344
They're just saying that
to get you off their back.

00:38:15.344 --> 00:38:16.530
They don't really want to.

00:38:16.530 --> 00:38:19.830
And in that case, it's very
hard because they really just

00:38:19.830 --> 00:38:23.502
don't really want to.

00:38:23.502 --> 00:38:26.240
You know, I should stop
drinking so much coffee.

00:38:26.240 --> 00:38:28.547
But I don't really intend
to stop drinking coffee.

00:38:28.547 --> 00:38:29.380
So that's one thing.

00:38:29.380 --> 00:38:31.810
But often people really
do want to change

00:38:31.810 --> 00:38:33.560
and they're frustrated
because they can't.

00:38:33.560 --> 00:38:35.184
And I think in that
case, you can help.

00:38:35.184 --> 00:38:37.996
And one way you can help is if
the person-- for many people,

00:38:37.996 --> 00:38:39.620
not for rebels, but
for everybody else,

00:38:39.620 --> 00:38:41.630
and particularly obligers.

00:38:41.630 --> 00:38:43.020
Crucially for obligers.

00:38:43.020 --> 00:38:44.710
External accountability
is helpful.

00:38:45.210 --> 00:38:48.320
So if you see a person
who is struggling,

00:38:48.320 --> 00:38:49.880
maybe help them
get accountability.

00:38:49.880 --> 00:38:51.630
You could act as an
accountability partner

00:38:51.630 --> 00:38:54.670
or you can figure out
whatever the behavior is,

00:38:54.670 --> 00:38:57.830
what would the accountability
be and build that in.

00:38:57.830 --> 00:39:01.480
Another thing is to do
the behavior yourself.

00:39:01.480 --> 00:39:03.580
Because in the strategy
of other people--

00:39:03.580 --> 00:39:07.464
I talk about this-- we swiftly
pick up habits from each other.

00:39:07.464 --> 00:39:10.130
And this is why you want to hang
out with people who have habits

00:39:10.130 --> 00:39:11.500
that you like, because
their habits are

00:39:11.500 --> 00:39:12.380
going to rub off on you.

00:39:12.380 --> 00:39:14.170
Your habits are going
to rub off on them.

00:39:14.170 --> 00:39:17.980
I had a funny experience
because every year we

00:39:17.980 --> 00:39:19.720
go on a beach vacation
with my in-laws,

00:39:19.720 --> 00:39:21.710
but this year I went on
my book tour instead.

00:39:21.710 --> 00:39:24.000
So they all went without me.

00:39:24.000 --> 00:39:26.520
And my husband texted me
after three days and he said,

00:39:26.520 --> 00:39:27.332
you're not here.

00:39:27.332 --> 00:39:29.290
Everything's starting an
hour and a half later.

00:39:29.290 --> 00:39:30.365
[LAUGHTER]

00:39:30.365 --> 00:39:31.870
Because I'm an early riser.

00:39:31.870 --> 00:39:34.120
And I'm the one saying, I'm
getting a little hungry.

00:39:34.120 --> 00:39:35.370
Are you guys ready for dinner?

00:39:35.370 --> 00:39:36.830
And everything would start.

00:39:36.830 --> 00:39:39.550
So one person was affecting
the habits of five people.

00:39:39.550 --> 00:39:41.590
Not because I was actually
shaking them awake

00:39:41.590 --> 00:39:43.330
in the morning, but
just because I--

00:39:43.330 --> 00:39:44.090
So our habits.

00:39:44.090 --> 00:39:45.590
So if you have good
habits yourself,

00:39:45.590 --> 00:39:46.790
that's going to be helpful.

00:39:46.790 --> 00:39:49.660
But another really, really
good way to be helpful

00:39:49.660 --> 00:39:51.660
is to make a habit
more convenient.

00:39:51.660 --> 00:39:57.410
We are crazily influenced by
how convenient or inconvenient.

00:39:57.410 --> 00:40:00.030
These are twin strategies,
convenience and inconvenience.

00:40:00.030 --> 00:40:02.377
If you don't want
someone to do something,

00:40:02.377 --> 00:40:03.460
make it very inconvenient.

00:40:03.460 --> 00:40:04.900
If you want them
to do something,

00:40:04.900 --> 00:40:06.700
make it as convenient
as possible.

00:40:06.700 --> 00:40:09.400
And this is where another
person can play a role.

00:40:09.400 --> 00:40:11.840
So if you're like, you're
not taking your medication,

00:40:11.840 --> 00:40:13.477
can I get one of
those trays where

00:40:13.477 --> 00:40:14.935
it's divided into
days of the week,

00:40:14.935 --> 00:40:17.280
and can I load it up every
week so that it's all there?

00:40:17.280 --> 00:40:18.700
And can I put in front
of the coffee pot,

00:40:18.700 --> 00:40:20.020
so if you're going to have
coffee in the morning,

00:40:20.020 --> 00:40:21.530
you're going to have to
have your pill first?

00:40:21.530 --> 00:40:22.909
And can I stand
there and say I'm

00:40:22.909 --> 00:40:24.200
going to check it off the list?

00:40:24.200 --> 00:40:25.100
[LAUGHTER]

00:40:25.100 --> 00:40:25.975
You know what I mean?

00:40:25.975 --> 00:40:28.180
Because the more you
make it convenient,

00:40:28.180 --> 00:40:30.310
the more it's going
to make it easy to do.

00:40:30.310 --> 00:40:32.930
And I had this
experience because I

00:40:32.930 --> 00:40:35.250
wanted to help my
now 16 year-old form

00:40:35.250 --> 00:40:38.800
the habit of working on her
homework on Sunday morning.

00:40:38.800 --> 00:40:43.180
Getting up early and doing
some solid work before the day

00:40:43.180 --> 00:40:43.880
went on.

00:40:43.880 --> 00:40:45.660
And she agreed to
do this, but you

00:40:45.660 --> 00:40:47.940
can imagine it wasn't
something that was

00:40:47.940 --> 00:40:50.690
naturally attractive to her.

00:40:50.690 --> 00:40:53.920
And so I make it as
convenient as possible.

00:40:53.920 --> 00:40:56.330
I wake her up gently.

00:40:56.330 --> 00:40:59.810
I help her carry her
stuff up into my office,

00:40:59.810 --> 00:41:01.332
because I work next
to her, which is

00:41:01.332 --> 00:41:02.540
the strategy of other people.

00:41:02.540 --> 00:41:04.610
She's working, I'm
working on Sunday morning.

00:41:04.610 --> 00:41:07.480
And I bring her breakfast
on a tray with her cup

00:41:07.480 --> 00:41:10.210
of tea and her whole breakfast.

00:41:10.210 --> 00:41:12.140
If she's chilly, I
get her a blanket.

00:41:12.140 --> 00:41:14.370
I want to make it as easy
and pleasant as possible

00:41:14.370 --> 00:41:17.560
so that I grease the
wheels of that habit.

00:41:17.560 --> 00:41:21.000
So those are some things
that a person can do.

00:41:21.000 --> 00:41:23.560
But if it's an obliger, the
absolutely crucial thing

00:41:23.560 --> 00:41:25.539
is to help them figure
out how to build

00:41:25.539 --> 00:41:26.830
in the external accountability.

00:41:26.830 --> 00:41:28.450
Because for so many
obligers, that's

00:41:28.450 --> 00:41:32.320
just the thing that just
unleashes whatever the habit is

00:41:32.320 --> 00:41:33.856
that they're trying to form.

00:41:33.856 --> 00:41:36.380
AUDIENCE: What's your
view on addiction?

00:41:36.380 --> 00:41:39.000
So people who are
not necessarily

00:41:39.000 --> 00:41:42.180
abstainers or moderators,
but overdoers?

00:41:42.180 --> 00:41:45.780
And it seems like a
core nature thing?

00:41:45.780 --> 00:41:51.137
So how would they break
that [INAUDIBLE] trait?

00:41:51.137 --> 00:41:52.720
GRETCHEN RUBIN: Well,
what do you mean

00:41:52.720 --> 00:41:55.170
by overdoers versus addicts?

00:41:55.170 --> 00:41:59.120
AUDIENCE: So I guess
to me, addiction's

00:41:59.120 --> 00:42:01.780
characterized by
overdoing and not

00:42:01.780 --> 00:42:03.060
able to moderate or abstain.

00:42:03.060 --> 00:42:04.160
GRETCHEN RUBIN:
Right, right, right.

00:42:04.160 --> 00:42:05.670
Well, that's a very
interesting question.

00:42:05.670 --> 00:42:07.880
And I've looked a lot at
these studies of addiction

00:42:07.880 --> 00:42:09.760
because it's very
related to habits

00:42:09.760 --> 00:42:11.780
and particularly how
people overcome addiction.

00:42:11.780 --> 00:42:13.310
In the book, I don't
talk about addiction.

00:42:13.310 --> 00:42:15.600
I don't talk about addiction,
compulsion, disorders,

00:42:15.600 --> 00:42:18.100
or nervous habits, so things
like hair twisting or nail

00:42:18.100 --> 00:42:21.680
biting, which to me are
seen very different.

00:42:21.680 --> 00:42:24.840
And it's controversial whether
addiction is even real.

00:42:24.840 --> 00:42:27.030
Many people argue that
there isn't really

00:42:27.030 --> 00:42:29.060
"addiction" in the way
that we think of it now,

00:42:29.060 --> 00:42:32.200
which is a fairly new idea.

00:42:32.200 --> 00:42:34.820
But I think that the
line between addiction

00:42:34.820 --> 00:42:36.800
and abstainers is interesting.

00:42:36.800 --> 00:42:40.250
Because for a lot of
people, it's all or nothing.

00:42:40.250 --> 00:42:42.190
There is no middle ground.

00:42:42.190 --> 00:42:46.550
And so I think one of
the interesting things

00:42:46.550 --> 00:42:53.230
that in knowing when do you
need to control something that

00:42:53.230 --> 00:42:55.770
seems like you're overdoing
it to other people,

00:42:55.770 --> 00:42:59.360
is do you feel like this
is enriching your life?

00:42:59.360 --> 00:43:01.280
Do you feel like this
behavior is good for you

00:43:01.280 --> 00:43:03.790
and making your life
richer and more complete?

00:43:03.790 --> 00:43:05.470
Or do you feel
like it's actually

00:43:05.470 --> 00:43:08.499
dragging you down and making you
feel full of guilt and remorse?

00:43:08.499 --> 00:43:10.540
And this is actually
sometimes very hard to tell.

00:43:10.540 --> 00:43:13.541
I know several people who,
other people around them

00:43:13.541 --> 00:43:15.540
would be like, you've got
an exercise addiction.

00:43:15.540 --> 00:43:17.000
You exercise too much.

00:43:17.000 --> 00:43:18.840
But they're like, this is great.

00:43:18.840 --> 00:43:19.340
I love it.

00:43:19.340 --> 00:43:20.190
I see my friends.

00:43:20.190 --> 00:43:21.620
I have all these
accomplishments.

00:43:21.620 --> 00:43:22.953
I love it, I love it, I love it.

00:43:22.953 --> 00:43:23.950
I'm out in nature.

00:43:23.950 --> 00:43:27.160
To them, it's enriching.

00:43:27.160 --> 00:43:30.270
It's not constraining
their lives.

00:43:30.270 --> 00:43:33.080
So sometimes what looks like
an addiction to one person

00:43:33.080 --> 00:43:36.270
isn't for another.

00:43:36.270 --> 00:43:42.517
But yeah, this idea
of do you manage--

00:43:42.517 --> 00:43:44.350
and I just have to say
as an abstainer, that

00:43:44.350 --> 00:43:45.350
just seems easier to me.

00:43:45.350 --> 00:43:49.230
It's hard for me even to think
of the mindset of somebody who

00:43:49.230 --> 00:43:52.004
would fight the desire
to overdo something

00:43:52.004 --> 00:43:52.920
by doing a little bit.

00:43:52.920 --> 00:43:54.546
Because that just
seems so challenging.

00:43:54.546 --> 00:43:56.753
But for some people, that's
really what works better.

00:43:56.753 --> 00:43:57.462
AUDIENCE: Thanks.

00:43:57.462 --> 00:43:58.753
So thanks for coming to Google.

00:43:58.753 --> 00:44:00.700
I'm a huge fan of "The
Happiness Project."

00:44:00.700 --> 00:44:01.030
GRETCHEN RUBIN: Oh, thank you.

